article.headline: TCU shoots just 31 percent from field
article.story:
FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Tasha Butts and Tennessee's defense
more than made up for a mistake-filled game Friday night.

Butts scored 19 points and the fifth-ranked Lady Vols overcame a
season-high 24 turnovers to hold off No. 19 TCU 74-66.

"There was no way this game was going to be pretty at the pace
it was being played," Tennessee coach Pat Summitt said of the game
played mostly at a frenetic rate. "It was ugly at times, but I'll
take an ugly win and smile about it."

Tennessee (9-1) is 211-19 since the 1997 NCAA tournament, a
winning percentage of better than 91 percent.

Despite the miscues, the Lady Vols held the Lady Frogs to a
season-low 31 percent from the field (19-of-58) and forced them
into 21 turnovers.

TCU (10-2) missed 20 of 21 shots in a 17-minute span that
allowed Tennessee to build a 13-point lead in the second half.

Butts made sure Tennessee cashed in on its defensive effort with
her best offensive game. She hit her first five shots and scored
six points in the final 3 minutes after TCU had cut Tennessee's
lead to single digits.

"My game starts with defense and rebounding," said Butts, who
scored 16 points Wednesday against George Washington. "I got my
first basket off a steal. After that, I just tried to stay poised
and patient."

Butts scored on a layup to put Tennessee ahead 68-60 with less
than 2 minutes left.

TCU responded with consecutive baskets to cut the lead to 68-64
with 1:18 remaining.

But the Lady Vols calmed the rally when Butts four straight free
throws and LaToya Davis converted a steal into a layup with 49
seconds remaining.

Tennessee's Shyra Ely, who had 15 points and 15 rebounds, fouled
out with 3:01 left. She then got a technical foul arguing the call
and TCU made three of the four free throws to come within 65-60.

"Tennessee is such a good team because they've been in
situations like this," TCU coach Jeff Mittie said. "They're
familiar with going on the road and handling the best shots from
other teams."

Tracy Wynn scored 12 points for the Lady Frogs, and Kim Ortega
and Ebony Shaw each had 11, while Sandora Irvin added nine points
and 13 rebounds.

Ortega hit a 3-pointer to bring TCU within 25-24 midway through
the first half, but the Lady Frogs, who had their four-game winning
streak snapped, went into its offensive funk as the Lady Vols
stretched their lead to 48-35 with 13:35 left in the game.
